school, and the figure rose to an appalling 45 per cent for post-graduate respondents.<br>Blaming the victim is an argument repeated across classes-whether in five star soirees, in campuses or in buses. It is echoed in bedrooms and in boardrooms. As a handmade slogan held aloft during the December 16 agitation said: Don't tell us not to be raped. Tell the men not to rape us.<br><br>What has allowed men to behave as if they are weak, unthinking creatures who could so easily be undone by a raised hem or a lowered cleavage? Perhaps it is because everything in popular culture conspires to make men believe they can get away with anything as long as they call it love. Take this year's sleeper hit, Raanjhanaa, in which stalking is romanticised as one man's ardent passion, never mind the woman is not interested. <br><br>He follows her around, holds her hand against her will, even slashes his wrists for her, all because he has dedicated his love to her (as his friend tells him, Tumhara pyaar na ho gaya. UPSC ka exam ho gaya. Dus saal se paas hi nahi ho raha-It's like a 10-year attempt to clear the UPSCexam). Or take Rowdy Rathore, where the hero calls his heroine mera maal and indicates that her special talent lies in her waist. Charming.<br><div style="border:0px solid #d7d7d7; margin:2px 0px 2px 15px;  width:300px; float:right"><div style="width:300px"><img vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0" align="right" style="border:1px solid #d7d7d7; margin:2px 2px" valign="top" title="" alt="" src="http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories//2013december/untitled-2_2_120513063101.jpg"></div></div><br>In many relationships, obsession becomes as real as violence, something that the immortal dialogue in Dabanng captured beautifully: Thappad se darr nahin lagta saabji, pyaar se lagta hai. Bollywood's misogynistic men are no longer villainous-they can be celebrated dudes, heroes played by rising stars like Arjun Kapoor in Ishaqzaade, where he deceives a young Muslim woman into having sex with him. When does love cross the line and violence take over? Popular culture with its Honey Singh lyrics and heroes spouting dialogues on mardangi (as in Goliyon Ki Rasleela Ram-leela) has blurred the boundaries.<br><br>The reality is harsh. The sex survey shows that the sense of entitlement to sex becomes stronger in marriage: 79 per cent of the men surveyed believed that it is their marital right to have sex. Post Tehelka, some hysterical masculinists have been complaining about the bedroom becoming criminalised. It's time they realised what happens in the bedroom no longer stays in the bedroom.<br><div style="border:0px solid #d7d7d7; margin:2px 15px 2px 0px;  width:540px; float:center"><div style="width:540px"><img vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0" align="middle" style="border:1px solid #d7d7d7; margin:2px 2px" valign="top" title="" alt="" width="540"src="http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories//2013december/untitled-3_03_120513063101.jpg"></div></div><br>Follow the writer on Twitter @kavereeb
